  doi = {10.1029/JC075i021p04161},
  abstract = {Individual daily vertical profiles of temperature through the first thousand meters above twenty-two antarctic bases are used to assess the mean strength of the surface temperature inversion on a monthly and seasonal basis. The profiles reveal a strong negative correlation between inversion strength and surface air temperature on both a day-to-day and a month-to-month basis for individual stations and between stations for the winter months. A method is described whereby the limited inversion data available may be supplemented by inferences from the much greater volume of surface temperature information in order to delineate the distribution of mean inversion strength on the plateau, the glacial slopes, and the major ice shelves of Antarctica. It is used to prepare a chart of the climatological mean inversion strength in winter when it exceeds 15\textdegree C over 80\% of the total area of the continent, with greatest strength of about 25\textdegree C over the highest parts of East Antarctica.},
